<Review ID>4792078
<Product Name>Philips HDD1630 6 GB MP3 Player
<Title>Decent MP3 player
<Date>Tue Jan 02 00:00:00 CST 2007
<Content>While I really prefer listening to music on actual CDs, I bought this MP3 player for the convenience of being able to take several albums of music with me in a small player rather lugging around a bulky CD wallet. I'm not a fan of ipods at all, and the Philips player is a nice alternative. The player itself, while not as compact as an ipod, is certainly small enough to fit inside your pocket or backpack. Also, the player itself feels very sturdy, and it can handle getting knocked around better than some other players out there on the market.  The interface is easy enough to navigate, although the touch-sensor buttons are a little too touchy, but that's nothing serious. The sound quality is just fine, although you might want to invest in some bigger headphones to get a fuller sound. The installation was very easy, and there was no problem loading the player with songs. The player I bought has 8 GB, not 6, which is more than enough space. I don't see how anyone could really need 30-80 gigs of music with them, except if they just like the novelty of having an insane amount of music with them.  The only issue I have with the player is it seems to occasionally have problems playing protected files. Most of the time it plays fine, but every so often it freezes up or takes several minutes to load a protected song. This is a non-issue if you just rip CDs to it, but if you use any sort of online service, it may freeze up from time to time. It usually unfreezes by itself, although a couple times I had to reformat the hard drive, and once had to just let the battery die out.  Despite this, the player plays fine 99% of the time. The Philips player is a fine alternative to the overpriced ipod.  
<Overall>4

