<Review ID>8848535
<Product Name>Philips HDD1630 6 GB MP3 Player
<Title>All's well....until last week.
<Date>Thu Oct 19 00:00:00 CST 2006
<Content>My parents bought me the Philips GoGear last Christmas. The player was wonderful. Everything I wanted on it, I had space for, and it didn't cost much. The screen wasn't as big as the Toshiba I had been wanting, but when I got my hands on it, I really enjoyed it.  All was well. I had to restart it maybe once after it froze, but that was not too much of a problem.  Everything was going perfectly, until late last week.  I had bought a new pair of earbuds because my Sony earbuds had started to static (my second pair since the original Philips earbuds), and when I put them in I realized I was getting the same problem: static and no sound. In a brand new pair of earbuds, I realized, as I hadn't before, that it wasn't the earbuds, but the player.  One morning on my way to school I tried to turn on my Philips.  After holding the power button for about 10 seconds (only supposed to be 3), I was greeted with a warning message telling me to connect my mp3 player to my computer.  All my music had been erased.  So when I get home, I redo the music, format it, and reinstall the software. It seemed okay, but it still took long for it to come on, but it did.  Now, just today, I try to turn on my Philips but there is nothing.  I give it to a friend to try to turn in on, and he shakes it.  There is a rattling inside the player.  I would call Philips to get a new player, but they put the serial number on a sticker on the back of the player, which naturally, as time goes on, becomes unreadable.  So now I am stuck with a useless mp3 player, and no serial number to get a new one.  
<Overall>2

