<Review ID>9405241
<Product Name>Philips HDD1630 6 GB MP3 Player
<Title>A lot of flash, but no bang.  Caveat emptor, i.e., buyer beware!
<Date>Fri Nov 25 00:00:00 CST 2005
<Content>I purchased this item as an alternative to the iPOD nano b/c of its looks and 6GB hard drive.  Those considerations did not help much at all, however, when I could not get the device to sync properly with Windows Media Player 10 ("WMP 10").  The music showed up on WMP 10 when the device was plugged to my USB port, but did not when it was not connected.  Altogether, I wasted about 3 hours trying to add music to this player after installing the Phillips plug-ins, but to no avial.  I would not recommend this player to anyone who seeks a user friendly product.  Save the time and consider another product.  It is really too bad that this design amounts to little of nothing in the end.  I gave it one star so that I could emphasize the fact that it is a NEGATIVE star.  I certainly hope that this saves you the time.  For the record... I am somewhat computer savvy, and that did not help me at all.  The old maxim "caveat emptor" ("buyer beware") definitely applies to this product.  -GCB  
<Overall>1

<Review ID>0091398
<Product Name>Philips HDD1630 6 GB MP3 Player
<Title>Great product!
<Date>Sun Nov 27 00:00:00 CST 2005
<Content>I felt I needed to write this review to clear up a few negative comments made:  "The music showed up on WMP 10 when the device was plugged to my USB port, but did not when it was not connected."  -Not quite clear what you are saying here.  Do you mean the music residing on the HDD1630 or music residing on your hard drive?  Music on any MP3 player WILL NOT show up in the device explorer when you unplug it from your computer.  "Altogether, I wasted about 3 hours trying to add music to this player after installing the Phillips plug-ins, but to no avial."  -You actually do not need the plugin to use your player.  I have used my HDD1630 on multiple computers and did not need the plugin to sync/view music with Media Player 10.  "Loading music is anything but simple because installation of the factory software is mandatory in order to add files to the device."  -This is a false statement if using Windows XP and Media Player 10.  Even WITHOUT the factory software, the HDD1630 will show us as a another drive in Windows Explorer (if you like dragging and dropping...although you need Media Player or something like Napster to transfer encrypted WMA files to ANY player).  Also, WITHOUT the factory software, you can transfer files with Media Player by using the Sync function.  "When connected to a PC's USB port, the device isn't assigned a temporary drive letter for easy file transfer using drag and drop."  -As stated above, when using Windows XP, the device WILL show up as another drive in Explorer (which is more than I can say for the Dell Jukebox which requires it's Explorer plugin installed to even view it)  Please note that I have not tested the HDD1630 with earlier operating systems.  "The quality of the color screen is comparable to an early color cell phone - (something similar to the Nokia 0001 model)"  -Please leave opinions out of reviews.  People, like me, use reviews to help them make the correct decision, based on their requirements in a product, when making a purchase.  Using opinions in your reviews is like saying "Don't buy apples because they taste bad."  (I'm going to go against what I just said, but for the purpose of debate, when viewing pictures with the HDD1630, they looked just as good as when viewing them with my digital camera display.)  My Review:  Positive: 1)  Great style 2)  Easy navigation 3)  Easy to add audio files using only the basic programs offered with Windows XP (any edition) 4)  Photos looked good when viewing them on the HDD1630  Negative: 1) Data and Power cable can not be detached from themselves, which is annoying when wanting to ONLY charge player or ONLY transfer files. 2) Maybe others had better luck, but the radio reception was poor with the builtin FM tuner. 3) Rubber protective sleeve covered up the data/power port (I used a razor bladed to cut open a hole so I didn't have to remove the sleeve when charging/transfering files).  Overall:  Good product and accessories.  Checkout the docking cradle with IR remote control.  
<Overall>4

<Review ID>3727320
<Product Name>Philips HDD1630 6 GB MP3 Player
<Title>I love this player, I took back my iPod 30gb video for it!
<Date>Fri Dec 09 00:00:00 CST 2005
<Content>First off iPod is by no means a bad product, it just didn't have what I wanted.  An FM tuner and the ability to obtain my music from somewhere other than iTunes. This is the sweetest little player I've ever seen or played with.  I also tried a creative Zen touch, the software was a nightmare.  The software for the GoGear is easy and fun.  I would suggest doing a manual sync or you might get tunes you don't want.  The FM tuner is awesome and I have no trouble picking up and adding all my favorite stations.  The screen allows you to choose between two background skins and you can run a photo slideshow while you listen.  It automatically finds album art which comes up when the song is playing, if you're not using the photo slide show. Philips offers a great case as well as a docking station for the GoGear. With the exception that it is not compatible with [...] and hopefully it will be eventually, the Philips 6GB GoGear is an incredible, overlooked player.  Did I mention you can record both voice and FM with it?  What more is there to say, a great player for those looking for an alternative to the iPod and other well known brands.  Give it a try I promise you won't be sorry!   
<Overall>5

<Review ID>9035834
<Product Name>Philips HDD1630 6 GB MP3 Player
<Title>The best PlaysForSure mp3 player
<Date>Fri Dec 09 00:00:00 CST 2005
<Content>I just got my hands on a Philips GoGear HDD1630 music player, and I have to say this is the best portable music player for you if youre interested in subscription based music (Napster, AOL MusicNow, Yahoo Music Unlimited etc).  The player does not require installation of any additional software on Windows XP (contrary to what the manual says). Just plug it into your XP SP2 computer, and XP should recognize the device, and you should be ready to go. I did not have to install any software to get this to work with Napster To Go or Windows Media player.  What I like:  1. Its looks The player itself is glossy black plastic, and feels very solid (like a slab of black granite). Unfortunately, it is VERY fingerprint prone - just dont let the FBI get their hands on it if youre in the run ;-) The player is very light, and will easily fight in your pocket or on an armband.  The backlight for the controls is blue in color, and looks very sexy.   2. The controls: The controls are very easy to use, and very sensitive. Navigation is very easy, just slide your finger up and down the strip.   3. Album art The player automatically syncs album art from Windows Media Player if the art is present on your computer. Thats a nice touch.  4. View pictures You can sync JPEG images to the player, and view them on the go.  5. Battery life The player lasts an average of 16-17 hours per charge - pretty cool!  What I dont like:  1. Since this is a relatively new player, accessories arent available.   2. Long-term support from Philips is questionable.   Overall, this is the best portable music player if youre interested in PlaysForSure (subsciption music). It poses some serious competition to the Ipod Nano, and is highly recommended.  
<Overall>5

