<Review ID>9686253
<Product Name>Philips HDD1630 6 GB MP3 Player
<Title>Great player, until it crashed and burned...
<Date>Sun Dec 25 00:00:00 CST 2005
<Content>I got this player last year for christmas, and for the most part was fairly happy with it, until a few months later it suddenly died. It was never dropped or misused in anyway. But if you are looking to buy this, please consider the good and bad.  The good:  -Very sleek design, although the black finish has a tendency to amplify any wear and tear (not to mention fingerprints)  -The intuitive interface is exetremely easy to use and remember (although it can get to be a minor annoyance when you forget to enable the hold button)  -Decent capacity for the hard drive it carries vs. other 6gb players. The programing (which is present when you buy the player that accounts for that space you couldn't fit that last gotta have song on it) doesn't actually take up much space, leaving you with more space for what's really important: MUSIC!!!  -You have the ability to place pictures on the device, albeit this can get somewhat confusing since you have to use windows media plays for sure programing and the software (included) vs. drag and drop (so much less time consuming) to actually add your pics to your player.  -USB 2.0 makes for some quick downloads to the hardware after you've finally got everything you want on windows media. (tip: try getting all the music/photo files you want in one folder, the adding it to your playlist and synch the playlist directly to the device. This also saves time in the future of it dumps)   OK, I tried hard to think of the good of the GoGear HDD 1630. And Honestly for the short few months that i did have it, I loves it more then my wife, BUT this device does have some major and critical problems:  -You can take perfect care of it and it will still give you problems.  -There is some MAJOR lag times in between screens, sometimes worse then on my home PC.  -Song transition can take up to four or more seconds when manually skipping through tracks.  -Customer service is outright terrible. Representitives are rude and unhelpfull and require you to pay for shipping and handling both ways to just look at the player and decide whether or not it is viable for them to fix it or replace it with a refurbished player, with a tirn around time of one to three plus months. (and I'm sorry with a possibility of downloading porn onto the player I really dont wish to take my chances with one that belonged to someone else, call me paranoid)  -Within the first hour of owning the GoGear, before even trying to load it with music it froze up on me and wouldn't turn off or do anything. I'm sorry but a brand new, out of the package device shouldn't require customer service withong the hour unless it was a thermo-nuclear bomb and it was counting down in my hand.  I really am trying to be fair in rating this problem, there are some awesome highlights to buying the Phillips GoGear Hdd1630. And in all honesty I would buy this product a second time around, considerering that the problems were fixed   
<Overall>2

