<Title>Nice Player, Horrible Software Interface
<Date>Thu May 18 00:00:00 CST 2006
<Content>No drag & drop -- You have to use Windows Media Player to organize, add, or remove files. The process is confusing, redundant, time-consuming and annoying. In order to add one or two songs to an extensive list of music already on the player, the entire list is "synchronized", wasting time and often losing some of the songs. Things can be apparently added or removed via the media player software, but later checking the device you find out they weren't. If you organize the playlists, the next time you add music, new playlists are created, even if you put the music into an older folder. If you have music and/or pictures in multiple folders on your computer harddrive, the player software insists on creating multiple folders on the device. It's nice once you get past the poor interface, but I'm not sure it's worth the headache.  If you're short-tempered, as I am, do not buy this player! You'll end up bashing it against the wall out of sheer frustration. (I haven't bashed it yet, but I've come close! ;)  
<Overall>2

<Review ID>3912519
<Product Name>Philips HDD1630 6 GB MP3 Player
<Title>Look Before You Leap
<Date>Thu May 18 00:00:00 CST 2006
<Content>I began searching for a digital audio player as an alternative to carrying around a suitcase of CDs when on the road.  I admit, what attracted me to the GoGear was the sleek, stylish look, the amount of hard disk memory, and price.  I didn't mind it being Windows XP (and .wma file) compatible because I had just recently purchased a brand new PC with XP as the operating system, with Windows Media Player standard and already loaded.  That to me made it the perfect fit.  After about a month of normal use and functioning properly for the most part, the first one froze up on me completely, unable to be reset or reset itself.  Tech support couldn't tell me a single thing that I hadn't already figured out on my own.  After sending it off for repair, Philips told me to allow 15-30 days for return.  My third contact/inquiry with them was after it had been over *60* days from the date of shipment.  About a week later, I ended up getting a brand new one as a replacement, so it's hard to argue with that.  The problem that I have with both units is that once I get the hard disk about 2/3 full, it has a tendency to "choke" and then "throw up" every single thing that I had loaded onto it.  When I would "Explore Device", WMP would show me everything that (I thought) I had just loaded onto it as normal, but when I disconnected the device, it showed all lists as empty.  Extremely annoying and frustrating when you've spent an hour or two trying to load the thing up and thinking you're good to go.  Here's how I remedied my problem...when I finally got a free day, I "babysat".  Instead of trying to synchronize 200-300 songs at a time, I would synchronize no more than 30-40 songs at a time, and when I had completed synchronizing each letter in the alphabet, I would disconnect the device, let it load up, check the contents, and then listen to at least one song in it's entirety.  Overkill, to be sure.  But it worked.  I ended up loading over 1200 songs (@ 128 kbps) into the GoGear, and it plays just fine...for now.  It took me the better half of daylight to do it (towards the end, it got reaaaallly SLOOOW), but after shelling out two hundred bucks, I had more time than money.  I personally think that the headphones are stellar, but I can see how someone having trouble getting or keeping them in their ears properly might think otherwise.  The sound quality is very good.  The battery life is excellent.  The 5-band EQ is another great feature that comes in especially handy when using the player for the main reason I bought it (playing it through your car stereo).    The sensory touchpad is at times a little too sensitive and other times not sensitive enough, but the navigation system is easy to use and pretty quick.  The USB connector and AC battery charger being one in the same cord is both a gift and a curse.  The protective pouch comes in handy, and you had better use it because the unit is pretty small and kind of slippery to boot (read: prone to be dropped).  The FM tuner works great outdoors, OK indoors.  I've never tried to load a picture onto it or use the voice recorder, and probably never will.  I personally found a happy medium, but as much as I want to, I can't wholeheartedly endorse this player with a clear conscience, let alone recommend it.  It's actually a pretty good player once you get it to do what you want, but WMP and the ineptitude and turnaround time of tech support notwithstanding, the software is way too buggy and the process I had to go through in order to get it to work (for me) is way too time consuming to make it anything more than satisfactory.  Not to mention that I literally shudder at the thought of another freeze-up or adding even one more song to it at this point.  Update: Six weeks later, the process is still very buggy, but we're now up to 1300 songs and no more crashes, so I guess that's worth another half-star. :-)  3.5 Stars   
<Overall>3

